Detection Story: LSASS Credential Access → Suspicious SMB Activity

Overview
This detection scenario focuses on identifying a common attacker objective: credential access via LSASS memory, followed by potential credential usage over the network.
Instead of stopping at a single alert, this scenario shows endpoint behavior with network activity to better understand attacker intent and progression.

Attack Simulation
The simulated attacker already has access to a Windows system with administrative privileges, and attempts to dump credentials from LSASS memory.
This is performed using a common administrative tool:

procdump.exe -ma lsass.exe C:\temp\lsass.dmp

After obtaining credentials (likely requiring Mimikatz or pypykatz usage to parse the produced dmp file), the attacker attempts to authenticate to another system over SMB:

net use \\TARGET_IP\C$ /user:Administrator ExamplePass123


Detection 1 — LSASS Memory Access (Endpoint)
LSASS is a high-value target because it stores credential material in memory. Access to this process is tightly controlled under normal conditions.
Using Sysmon ProcessAccess events (Event ID 10), we can identify when a process attempts to access LSASS.


SPL Query:

index=* sourcetype="WinEventLog:Microsoft-Windows-Sysmon/Operational"
EventCode=10 TargetImage="*lsass.exe"
| search SourceImage="*procdump.exe" OR SourceImage="*rundll32.exe"
| table _time Computer SourceImage TargetImage GrantedAccess
| sort -_time

This detection identifies processes attempting to interact with LSASS memory, which is a strong indicator of credential dumping activity.

Detection 2 — SMB Activity (Network)
After credential access, attackers often attempt to use harvested credentials for lateral movement.
To validate this behavior, Zeek connection logs were analyzed for SMB traffic (port 445):

SPL Query:

index=* sourcetype=zeek_conn
id.resp_p=445
| table _time id.orig_h id.resp_h id.resp_p proto
| sort -_time

This finds outbound SMB connection attempts originating from the same system that accessed LSASS.

Correlation Insight
By correlating endpoint and network telemetry, this detection shows a progression:
	•	A process accessed LSASS memory (credential access)
	•	The same system initiated SMB connections shortly afterward
	•	This pattern is consistent with early-stage lateral movement using harvested credentials
This multi-source approach provides stronger confidence than either signal alone.

MITRE ATT&CK Mapping
	•	T1003 — OS Credential Dumping
	•	T1021.002 — SMB/Windows Admin Shares
	•	T1550 — Use of Stolen Credentials

Outcome
This scenario shows how combining endpoint visibility (Sysmon) with network telemetry (Zeek) can reveal attacker intent and progression.
Rather than treating alerts in isolation, correlating activity across data sources helps distinguish real threats from noise and provides a clearer picture of what an attacker is attempting to achieve.

Key Takeaway
Credential access is rarely the end goal. By validating what happens immediately after, defenders can better detect and respond to attacker movement before it escalates further.
